{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641970"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:34:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:34:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17919"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17919"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.16,0.58,0.13,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10633"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76185"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10633"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17919"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61689"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5064"},{"type":"tags","id":"5098"},{"type":"tags","id":"5100"},{"type":"tags","id":"5371"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24770"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24773"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76185"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA patient presents with a new diagnosis of type 2 diabetes and would like to discuss different management options. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about the treatment of type 2 diabetes is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["SGLT2 inhibitors prevent intestinal glucose absorption","Side effects of metformin include weight gain and hypoglycaemia","SGLT2 inhibitors are unlikely to cause hypoglycaemia or weight gain","GLP-1 analogues are orally administered to stimulate insulin secretion","Lifestyle interventions are not preferred as they are largely unsuccessful"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESGLT2 inhibitors are unlikely to cause hypoglycaemia or weight gain\u003C/strong\u003E. These medications work by preventing glucose reabsorption in the kidneys, leading to glucose excretion in the urine. This mechanism is associated with weight loss and a low risk of hypoglycaemia when used as a monotherapy or in combination with other non-insulin therapies. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELifestyle interventions\u003C/strong\u003E, centred around diet and exercise, are a cornerstone in the management of type 2 diabetes and can be highly effective in improving glycaemic control and reducing cardiovascular risk factors. They are recommended as first-line therapy alongside pharmacological treatments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetformin\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with weight loss or weight neutrality and does not typically cause hypoglycaemia. It is the first-line pharmacological treatment for type 2 diabetes due to its efficacy, safety profile, and cardiovascular benefits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGLP-1 analogues\u003C/strong\u003E are medications that enhance insulin secretion, suppress glucagon release, and slow gastric emptying. They are delivered via subcutaneous injection. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lifestyle interventions are a cornerstone in the management of type 2 diabetes and can be highly effective.","Metformin is associated with weight loss or weight neutrality and is unlikely to cause hypoglycaemia.","GLP-1 analogues are medications delivered via subcutaneous injection that enhance insulin secretion, increase glucagon release and slow gastric emptying.","SGLT2 inhibitors work by preventing glucose reabsorption in the kidneys","SGLT2 inhibitors are associated with weight loss and are unlikely to cause hypoglycaemia"],"references":["Galicia-Garcia U, Benito-Vicente A, Jebari S, Larrea-Sebal A, Siddiqi H, Uribe KB, Ostolaza H, Mart\u00edn C. Pathophysiology of Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus. Int J Mol Sci. 2020 Aug 30;21(17):6275. doi: 10.3390/ijms21176275. PMID: 32872570; PMCID: PMC7503727","Wright EM. SGLT2 Inhibitors: Physiology and Pharmacology. Kidney360. 2021 Sep 17;2(12):2027-2037. doi: 10.34067/KID.0002772021. PMID: 35419546; PMCID: PMC8986039.","Aloke C, Egwu CO, Aja PM, Obasi NA, Chukwu J, Akumadu BO, Ogbu PN, Achilonu I. Current Advances in the Management of Diabetes Mellitus. Biomedicines. 2022 Sep 29;10(10):2436. doi: 10.3390/biomedicines10102436. PMID: 36289697; PMCID: PMC9599361."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61689"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17919"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61689"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T11:05:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T11:06:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10633"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76185"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemC